Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR -> JULIA TRANSLATOR
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Walks a HIRNode tree (rooted at HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION) and emits
Note: idiomatic Julia source code into an EmitterContext output buffer.

Note: Coverage:
Note:   - Module / function / struct / abstract-type declarations
Note:   - Let / Set / If / Match / For / While / Return / Break / Continue
Note:   - All expression forms: literals, identifiers, binary/unary/ternary,
Note:     calls, member access, array indexing, ranges, lambdas, casts
Note:   - Types: Basic, Generic, Function, Array, Tuple, Optional, Union

Note: Julia-specific conventions emitted:
Note:   - struct ... end blocks for HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION
Note:   - function name(args)::ReturnType ... end for HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION
Note:   - Optional types map to Union{T, Nothing}
Note:   - Integer/Float/String/Boolean to Int64/Float64/String/Bool
Note:   - Range expressions to a:b or a:step:b
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/emitter_common.runa" as Emitter
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE-NAME MAPPING TABLE
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Map Runa primitive type names to Julia equivalents. Other type identifiers
Note: pass through unchanged so user-defined types render verbatim.
@Reasoning:
Runa's primitive type spelling (Integer, Float, Boolean, Character)
differs from Julia's (Int64, Float64, Bool, Char). Mapping at code
emission keeps the HIR canonical while still producing idiomatic
Julia. Unknown names (user-defined types) pass through unchanged so
custom types render verbatim.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Linear sequence of string_equals comparisons. Integer/Integer64 map to
Int64; Integer8/16/32 retain their width. Float/Float64 map to
Float64; Float32 retains. String and Float32 keep their Runa name.
Boolean -> Bool, Character -> Char, Nothing -> Nothing. Falls through
to return runa_name on any unrecognised input.
@End Implementation

Process called "julia_map_basic_type" takes runa_name as String returns String:
    Let eq be 0

    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Integer"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Int64"
    End If

    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Integer8"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Int8"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Integer16"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Int16"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Integer32"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Int32"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Integer64"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Int64"
    End If

    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Float"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Float64"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Float32"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Float32"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Float64"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Float64"
    End If

    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "String"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "String"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Boolean"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Bool"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Character"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Char"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_name, "Nothing"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "Nothing"
    End If

    Return runa_name
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIRNode ACCESSORS
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Local wrappers over hir.runa accessors so the rest of the file reads as
Note: high-level walk logic without repeating memory_get_ noise.
Note: HIRNode layout (offsets, see hir.runa Type HIRNode):
Note:   0:  node_type   (Integer constant - see Constant HIR_*)
Note:   8:  line        (Integer source line)
Note:   16: column      (Integer source column)
Note:   24: children    (List[Integer] pointer)
Note:   32: child_count (Integer count)
Note:   40: value       (Integer or pointer to literal/identifier value)
Note:   48: value_type  (Integer subtype discriminator)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Null-safe accessor for HIRNode.node_type at offset 0. Used by emit_node
to discriminate which emit_* helper to dispatch to.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 0 (no valid HIR_* constant is zero). Otherwise
reads i64 at offset 0 via MemoryCore.memory_get_integer.
@End Implementation

Process called "node_type_of" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with node, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the polymorphic value slot at offset 40 — used differently
per node type: identifier name handle, literal value, operator code,
etc. Null-safe.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 0. Reads i64 at offset 40 of the HIRNode record.
@End Implementation

Process called "node_value" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with node, 40
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the value-subtype discriminator at offset 48 — used by
literal nodes to distinguish Integer/Float/String/Boolean values and by
operator nodes to discriminate +, -, *, etc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 0. Reads i64 at offset 48 of the HIRNode record.
@End Implementation

Process called "node_value_type" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with node, 48
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the child_count field at offset 32. Cached alongside the
children list so iteration code doesn't need to call list_size each
time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 0. Reads i64 at offset 32 of the HIRNode record.
@End Implementation

Process called "node_child_count" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with node, 32
End Process

@Reasoning:
Indexed child accessor: pulls the children list (offset 24) and looks
up the requested index. Both null-node and null-children-list are
handled, so callers can iterate up to node_child_count without
checking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard on node. Reads children pointer at offset 24; if null
returns 0 (empty-child case). Otherwise delegates to ListCore.list_get
with the index. Out-of-range index is the caller's responsibility.
@End Implementation

Process called "node_child" takes node as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with node, 24
    If children is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc list_get from ListCore with children, index
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Generate a complete Julia source string for the given HIR module. Returns
Note: the rendered text. Errors during translation are recorded on the context
Note: but do not abort - callers can inspect emitter_has_errors after the call.
@Reasoning:
Public driver for the Julia backend. Constructs a fresh EmitterContext
(with 4-space indent matching Julia community style), kicks off the
recursive node walker, and returns the accumulated output.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls Emitter.create_emitter_context to allocate output buffer and
counters. Recurses into emit_node with the module root. Returns
Emitter.emitter_get_output which exposes the accumulated string.
Errors are logged on the context rather than thrown so partial output
is still recoverable.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_julia_from_hir" takes hir_module as Integer returns String:
    Note: emitter_common defaults to 4-space indentation which matches the
    Note: Julia community style guide, so no override needed here.
    Let ctx be proc create_emitter_context from Emitter

    proc emit_node with ctx, hir_module

    Return proc emitter_get_output from Emitter with ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Single-arg wrapper matching the central dispatcher call shape in
Note: translation.runa: `Return proc hir_to_julia from JuliaEmitter with hir_root`.
Note: Delegates to generate_julia_from_hir which holds the actual translation
Note: pipeline. Kept as a separate name so the dispatcher contract stays stable
Note: even if the internal generator is renamed in the future.
@Reasoning:
Stable public entry name used by the central translation dispatcher in
translation.runa. Keeping this as a thin forwarder lets the internal
pipeline (generate_julia_from_hir) be renamed without breaking the
dispatcher contract.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single proc call: returns generate_julia_from_hir(hir_root).
@End Implementation

Process called "hir_to_julia" takes hir_root as Integer returns String:
    Return proc generate_julia_from_hir with hir_root
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCH
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-level node dispatcher. Branches on node_type to the appropriate
Note: emit_* helper. Unknown node types emit a "# TODO: HIR_<id>" comment and
Note: record a warning so the output is still valid Julia.

@Reasoning:
The universal HIR-node dispatcher: every other emit_* helper visits
a single node type, while children are recursed via this function.
Falls back to a TODO comment for unknown node kinds so the output
stays valid Julia even when the translator hits a node it doesn't
recognise.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard. Reads node_type via node_type_of. Long If/Return chain
dispatches each HIR_* constant to the matching emit_* helper
(emit_module, emit_function, emit_struct, emit_import, emit_let,
emit_set, emit_const, emit_if, emit_match, emit_for, emit_while,
emit_return, emit_block_children, emit_expression for expression
nodes). Unrecognised types emit a `# TODO: HIR_<id>` comment.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_node" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let nt be proc node_type_of with node

    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION:
        proc emit_module with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION:
        proc emit_function with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION:
        proc emit_struct with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_IMPORT_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_import with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_let with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_SET_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_set with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_const with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_IF_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_if with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_match with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_FOR_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_for with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_WHILE_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_while with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_RETURN_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_return with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_BREAK_STATEMENT:
        proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "break"
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_CONTINUE_STATEMENT:
        proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "continue"
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT:
        proc emit_block_children with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_EXPRESSION_STATEMENT:
        Let inner be proc node_child with node, 0
        proc emit_expression with ctx, inner
        proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
        Return
    End If

    Note: Default - treat as expression
    proc emit_expression with ctx, node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MODULE
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Wrap children in a Julia `module Name ... end` block.
@Reasoning:
Top-level modules emit Julia's `module Name ... end` syntax with a
`using Base` brought in by default so common operators are available
without explicit imports.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the module name from node_value via julia_string_from_pointer.
Emits `module <name>`, then `using Base`. Recurses emit_node over
each child. Emits `end # module <name>` closer with the name in a
comment to aid readability.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_module" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "module "
    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, name_str

    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "using Base"
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx

    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        proc emit_node with ctx, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "end # module "
    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, name_str
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IMPORTS
Note: ============================================================================
@Reasoning:
Runa imports map directly to Julia's `using` directive. The module
path string in node_value is preserved verbatim.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pulls path string from node_value via julia_string_from_pointer.
Emits `using <path>` followed by a newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_import" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let path_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let path_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with path_ptr
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "using "
    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, path_str
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRUCT / TYPE DEFINITION
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Emit:
Note:   struct Name
Note:       field1::Type1
Note:       field2::Type2
Note:   end
@Reasoning:
Runa Type declarations become Julia immutable structs. Each child node
of kind HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION renders as `name::Type` indented under
the struct keyword.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `struct <name>` line. Indents one level. Iterates children;
each one with node_type == HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION is dispatched to
emit_field. Other child kinds are skipped. Dedents and emits the
matching `end`, followed by a blank line.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_struct" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "struct "
    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, name_str

    proc emitter_indent from Emitter with ctx

    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let field be proc node_child with node, i
        Let ft be proc node_type_of with field
        If ft is equal to HIR.HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION:
            proc emit_field with ctx, field
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emitter_dedent from Emitter with ctx
    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "end"
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
A struct field renders as `name::Type`, with the type optional (omitted
emits just the bare name, matching Julia's untyped-field semantics).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads field name from node_value, emits it. If child 0 (the type
node) exists, emits `::` then calls emit_type on it. Trailing newline
to keep one field per line.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_field" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, name_str

    Let type_node be proc node_child with node, 0
    If type_node is not equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "::"
        proc emit_type with ctx, type_node
    End If

    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FUNCTION / PROCESS DEFINITION
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Emit:
Note:   function name(p1::T1, p2::T2)::ReturnT
Note:       body
Note:   end
@Reasoning:
HIR HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION nodes carry parameter Lets (typed) and an
optional return-type node together with a HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT body
in their children. The emitter walks the children once,
distinguishing params, return type, and body by node type and the
value_type flag (cvt==1 marks the return-type node).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `function <name>(`. Walks children: HIR_LET_STATEMENT children
are parameters — dispatched to emit_param with comma separators
between them (first_param flag handles the lead). HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT
child becomes body_node. Otherwise, cvt==1 marks the return_type_node.
After the param list emits `)`, optional `::<return>`, newline,
indented body via emit_block_children, dedent, `end`, blank line.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_function" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "function "
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, name_str
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "("

    Note: Child layout: param list nodes first, then optional return type
    Note: marked by node_value_type == 1, then a HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT body.
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let first_param be 1
    Let return_type_node be 0
    Let body_node be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        Let ct be proc node_type_of with child
        Let cvt be proc node_value_type with child

        If ct is equal to HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT:
            Note: param declaration encoded as a Let
            If first_param is equal to 0:
                proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ", "
            End If
            proc emit_param with ctx, child
            Set first_param to 0
        Otherwise:
            If ct is equal to HIR.HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT:
                Set body_node to child
            Otherwise:
                If cvt is equal to 1:
                    Set return_type_node to child
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ")"
    If return_type_node is not equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "::"
        proc emit_type with ctx, return_type_node
    End If
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx

    proc emitter_indent from Emitter with ctx
    If body_node is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_block_children with ctx, body_node
    End If
    proc emitter_dedent from Emitter with ctx

    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "end"
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Inline parameter renderer (no trailing newline or comma) used by
emit_function for each parameter position. Comma between params is
the caller's responsibility.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads parameter name from node_value and emits it. If child 0 (type
annotation) is non-zero, emits `::` then calls emit_type with the
type node.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_param" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, name_str

    Let type_node be proc node_child with node, 0
    If type_node is not equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "::"
        proc emit_type with ctx, type_node
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STATEMENTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Runa `Let name [as Type] be value` maps to Julia's
`name[::Type] = value`. Type is optional and detected via the cvt==1
discriminator on the child node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads variable name from node_value. Iterates children sorting them
into type_node (cvt==1) and init_node (everything else). If type
present, emits `::<type>`. If init present, emits ` = <expr>`. Ends
with a newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_let" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, name_str

    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let type_node be 0
    Let init_node be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        Let cvt be proc node_value_type with child
        If cvt is equal to 1:
            Set type_node to child
        Otherwise:
            Set init_node to child
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If type_node is not equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "::"
        proc emit_type with ctx, type_node
    End If
    If init_node is not equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, " = "
        proc emit_expression with ctx, init_node
    End If
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Runa's `Set target to value` becomes Julia's `target = value`. Both
operands are arbitrary expressions, dispatched through emit_expression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads child 0 as the LHS target and child 1 as the RHS value.
Emits `<target> = <value>` followed by a newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_set" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let target be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let value be proc node_child with node, 1

    proc emit_expression with ctx, target
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, " = "
    proc emit_expression with ctx, value
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Runa Constant declarations map to Julia's `const` global definition.
Julia const isn't lexically scoped, but for top-level constants the
semantics match closely enough.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads constant name from node_value. Emits `const <name> = ` then
child 0 (the initializer expression) via emit_expression. Trailing
newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_const" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "const "
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, name_str
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, " = "

    Let init_node be proc node_child with node, 0
    If init_node is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_expression with ctx, init_node
    End If
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Standard Julia if/else syntax with `end` closer. The HIR layout puts
condition at child 0, then-block at child 1, optional else-block at
child 2.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `if `, then the condition expression. Newline + indent. Recurses
into then-block via emit_block_children. Dedents. If child 2 exists,
emits `else` keyword, indents, recurses, dedents. Closes with `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_if" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Note: Layout: child 0 = condition, child 1 = then-block, optional child 2 = else-block
    Let cond be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let then_block be proc node_child with node, 1
    Let else_block be proc node_child with node, 2

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "if "
    proc emit_expression with ctx, cond
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx

    proc emitter_indent from Emitter with ctx
    If then_block is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_block_children with ctx, then_block
    End If
    proc emitter_dedent from Emitter with ctx

    If else_block is not equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "else"
        proc emitter_indent from Emitter with ctx
        proc emit_block_children with ctx, else_block
        proc emitter_dedent from Emitter with ctx
    End If

    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia's standard library has no built-in match expression; MLStyle.jl
provides one but requires an external dependency. For portability the
emitter lowers Runa Match to a chain of if/elseif comparing the subject
expression against each when-pattern.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads subject from child 0; child_count tells how many when-clauses
follow. Emits `let _subject = <subject>` to bind once. Indents.
Iterates remaining children, expecting HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE: child 0 is
the pattern, child 1 is the body. First arm emits `if _subject ==
<pattern>`, subsequent arms emit `elseif _subject == <pattern>`.
Body is indented under each arm. Closes with `end` for the let.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_match" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Note: Julia has no first-class match, but Match{} from MLStyle.jl matches
    Note: closely. For portability emit an if/elseif/else chain comparing the
    Note: subject to each when-pattern.
    Let subject be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "let _subject = "
    proc emit_expression with ctx, subject
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
    proc emitter_indent from Emitter with ctx

    Let first be 1
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than count:
        Let arm be proc node_child with node, i
        Let arm_type be proc node_type_of with arm
        If arm_type is equal to HIR.HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE:
            Let pattern be proc node_child with arm, 0
            Let body be proc node_child with arm, 1

            If first is equal to 1:
                proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "if _subject == "
            Otherwise:
                proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "elseif _subject == "
            End If
            proc emit_expression with ctx, pattern
            proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx

            proc emitter_indent from Emitter with ctx
            proc emit_node with ctx, body
            proc emitter_dedent from Emitter with ctx
            Set first to 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If first is equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "end"
    End If
    proc emitter_dedent from Emitter with ctx
    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Runa `For Each var in collection` maps to Julia's `for var in
collection`. The iteration variable is encoded as a Let node so the
parser can attach an optional type — only the name is used here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads child 0 (var Let), child 1 (collection expression), child 2
(body block). Extracts var name. Emits `for <var> in <collection>`
with newline. Indents, recurses body via emit_block_children, dedents,
closes with `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_for" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Note: For-each: child 0 = iteration variable Let, child 1 = collection expr,
    Note: child 2 = body block.
    Let var_decl be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let collection be proc node_child with node, 1
    Let body be proc node_child with node, 2

    Let var_name_ptr be proc node_value with var_decl
    Let var_name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with var_name_ptr

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "for "
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, var_name_str
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, " in "
    proc emit_expression with ctx, collection
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx

    proc emitter_indent from Emitter with ctx
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_block_children with ctx, body
    End If
    proc emitter_dedent from Emitter with ctx

    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Runa `While cond` maps directly to Julia's `while cond ... end`. No
parenthesisation needed because Julia parses the condition as the
expression following the keyword.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads condition (child 0) and body (child 1). Emits `while <cond>`
with newline, indents, recurses into body via emit_block_children,
dedents, closes with `end`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_while" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let cond be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let body be proc node_child with node, 1

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "while "
    proc emit_expression with ctx, cond
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx

    proc emitter_indent from Emitter with ctx
    If body is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_block_children with ctx, body
    End If
    proc emitter_dedent from Emitter with ctx

    proc emitter_emit_line from Emitter with ctx, "end"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia's return is a keyword followed by an optional expression. Bare
`return` returns `nothing` implicitly. A missing child 0 produces
exactly that.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `return`. Reads child 0; if non-zero, emits a space and the
expression. Trailing newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_return" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "return"
    Let value be proc node_child with node, 0
    If value is not equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, " "
        proc emit_expression with ctx, value
    End If
    proc emitter_emit_newline from Emitter with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Iteration helper used by every statement that has a body block:
walks the children list dispatching emit_node on each. Indentation
and the surrounding braces/keywords are the caller's responsibility.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads child_count, loops i = 0..count, calls emit_node with each
child.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_block_children" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child with node, i
        proc emit_node with ctx, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXPRESSIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Companion to emit_node but specialised for expression positions. Every
HIR expression kind that can appear inside another expression flows
through here. Null node degrades gracefully to `nothing`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-node fast path emits `nothing`. Then long Match on node_type:
LITERAL/IDENTIFIER/BINARY/UNARY/TERNARY/CALL/MEMBER/INDEX/
PARENTHESIZED/INTERPOLATED_STRING/RANGE/ARRAY_LITERAL/TUPLE_LITERAL/
LAMBDA/CAST dispatch to dedicated helpers. Unknown kinds fall through
to `_HIR_UNKNOWN_` placeholder with a warning recorded on the emitter
context — keeps output parseable as Julia.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_expression" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "nothing"
        Return
    End If

    Let nt be proc node_type_of with node

    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
        proc emit_literal with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
        Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, name_str
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPRESSION:
        proc emit_binary with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_UNARY_EXPRESSION:
        proc emit_unary with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_TERNARY_EXPRESSION:
        proc emit_ternary with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION:
        proc emit_call with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPRESSION:
        proc emit_member with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_INDEX_EXPRESSION:
        proc emit_index with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_PARENTHESIZED:
        Let inner be proc node_child with node, 0
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "("
        proc emit_expression with ctx, inner
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ")"
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_INTERPOLATED_STRING:
        proc emit_interpolated_string with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_RANGE_EXPRESSION:
        proc emit_range with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL:
        proc emit_array_literal with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL:
        proc emit_tuple_literal with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION:
        proc emit_lambda with ctx, node
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_CAST_EXPRESSION:
        proc emit_cast with ctx, node
        Return
    End If

    Note: Unknown expression kind: emit a placeholder identifier so Julia
    Note: parsing still succeeds and surface the issue via a warning.
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "_HIR_UNKNOWN_"
    proc emitter_warning from Emitter with ctx, "unhandled expression node type"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Literal nodes carry both the lexeme (value) and a subtype tag
(value_type) so the emitter knows whether to quote a string, normalise
a boolean, or emit `nothing` for null. Numeric lexemes pass through
verbatim because Julia accepts the same notation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads value_str via julia_string_from_pointer and vtype via
node_value_type. vtype dispatch: 2=string (wrap in `"..."`), 3=boolean
(normalise to literal `true`/`false` via string_equals match),
4=null (emit `nothing`). Default (covers 0=integer and 1=float)
emits value_str verbatim.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_literal" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let value_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let value_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with value_ptr
    Let vtype be proc node_value_type with node

    Note: vtype convention: 0=integer literal, 1=float literal, 2=string,
    Note: 3=boolean, 4=null. Strings need quoting; null maps to nothing.
    If vtype is equal to 2:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "\""
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, value_str
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "\""
        Return
    End If
    If vtype is equal to 3:
        Let is_true be proc string_equals from StringCore with value_str, "true"
        If is_true is equal to 1:
            proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "true"
        Otherwise:
            proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "false"
        End If
        Return
    End If
    If vtype is equal to 4:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "nothing"
        Return
    End If

    Note: Default: emit numeric literal verbatim
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, value_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary expressions in Julia use infix syntax. The operator string from
the HIR may need remapping (e.g. `equals` -> `==`); that's
julia_map_binary_op's job. Spaces around the operator match Julia
style.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads op string, runs julia_map_binary_op for the spelling. Pulls lhs
(child 0) and rhs (child 1). Emits `<lhs> <op> <rhs>` with single
spaces around the operator. Both sides recurse via emit_expression.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_binary" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let op_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let op_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with op_ptr
    Let mapped be proc julia_map_binary_op with op_str

    Let lhs be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let rhs be proc node_child with node, 1

    proc emit_expression with ctx, lhs
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, " "
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, mapped
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, " "
    proc emit_expression with ctx, rhs
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary expressions emit `<op><operand>` with no space (Julia convention).
Operator remapping handles `not` -> `!` and friends via
julia_map_unary_op.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads op string and runs julia_map_unary_op. Pulls operand (child 0).
Emits mapped op then recurses emit_expression on operand. No space
between them so `not x` becomes `!x` not `! x`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_unary" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let op_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let op_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with op_ptr
    Let mapped be proc julia_map_unary_op with op_str

    Let operand be proc node_child with node, 0

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, mapped
    proc emit_expression with ctx, operand
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia's ternary uses `cond ? then : else` syntax. The whole expression
is wrapped in parentheses so the result is safe to embed in any
parent context without precedence ambiguity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads cond/then_e/else_e from children 0/1/2. Emits
`(<cond> ? <then> : <else>)` with each part recursed via
emit_expression.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_ternary" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let cond be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let then_e be proc node_child with node, 1
    Let else_e be proc node_child with node, 2

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "("
    proc emit_expression with ctx, cond
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, " ? "
    proc emit_expression with ctx, then_e
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, " : "
    proc emit_expression with ctx, else_e
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ")"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function/method call syntax `callee(arg1, arg2, ...)`. Julia
distinguishes regular calls from member calls only by surface
syntax — the call expression itself is uniform.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads child 0 as callee; recurses to emit it. Emits `(`. Loops over
children 1..n-1 (each is an argument), emitting `, ` separators
between them via the i>1 check. Closes with `)`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_call" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Note: Child 0 = callee, children 1..n-1 = arguments
    Let callee be proc node_child with node, 0
    proc emit_expression with ctx, callee
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "("

    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than count:
        If i is greater than 1:
            proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ", "
        End If
        Let arg be proc node_child with node, i
        proc emit_expression with ctx, arg
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ")"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Member access `object.field` directly mirrors Runa's field-access
syntax. The field name comes from node_value rather than a child node
because there's only one field per access.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads object (child 0) and field name string. Emits the object,
`.`, then the field name.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_member" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let object be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let field_name_ptr be proc node_value with node
    Let field_name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with field_name_ptr

    proc emit_expression with ctx, object
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "."
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, field_name_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Indexing `collection[index]`. Julia uses 1-based indexing by default,
which the HIR builder is expected to have already normalised — this
emitter renders the index expression verbatim.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads collection (child 0) and index (child 1). Emits `<collection>[`,
the index expression, `]`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_index" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let collection be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let index be proc node_child with node, 1

    proc emit_expression with ctx, collection
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "["
    proc emit_expression with ctx, index
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "]"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia ranges use `start:end` or `start:step:end`. The HIR layout
puts start at child 0, end at child 1, and optional step at child 2.
The emitter inverts the conventional ordering at output time so the
step goes between start and end as Julia expects.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads start_e/end_e/step_e from children 0/1/2. Emits start; if step
present emits `:step`; then emits `:end`. Produces `start:end` for
no-step and `start:step:end` otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_range" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Note: Range layout: start, end, optional step
    Let start_e be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let end_e be proc node_child with node, 1
    Let step_e be proc node_child with node, 2

    proc emit_expression with ctx, start_e
    If step_e is not equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ":"
        proc emit_expression with ctx, step_e
    End If
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ":"
    proc emit_expression with ctx, end_e
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bracketed array literal `[a, b, c]`. Same syntax in Julia and Runa,
so each child expression is emitted with comma separators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `[`. Loops children, emitting `, ` between adjacent elements
via the i>0 check. Recurses each element via emit_expression. Closes
with `]`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_array_literal" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "["
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        If i is greater than 0:
            proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ", "
        End If
        Let elem be proc node_child with node, i
        proc emit_expression with ctx, elem
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "]"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia tuples are parenthesised: `(a, b, c)`. A single-element tuple
requires a trailing comma `(a,)` to disambiguate from a parenthesised
expression — the emitter handles that special case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits `(`. Loops children with `, ` separators. After the loop, if
count == 1, emits an extra `,` to mark it as a tuple. Closes with `)`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_tuple_literal" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "("
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        If i is greater than 0:
            proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ", "
        End If
        Let elem be proc node_child with node, i
        proc emit_expression with ctx, elem
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If count is equal to 1:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ","
    End If
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ")"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia anonymous functions use `(params) -> body` syntax. Parameters
come first as Let nodes, the body is always the last child — a layout
chosen so the body's position is computable from child_count - 1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes body_index = child_count - 1. Emits `(`. Loops i = 0..body_index
emitting each parameter via emit_param with `, ` separators. Emits
`) -> `. Recurses emit_expression on the body (child at body_index).
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_lambda" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Note: Last child is body, preceding children are param Let nodes.
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "("
    Let i be 0
    Let body_index be count minus 1
    While i is less than body_index:
        If i is greater than 0:
            proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ", "
        End If
        Let p be proc node_child with node, i
        proc emit_param with ctx, p
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ") -> "

    Let body be proc node_child with node, body_index
    proc emit_expression with ctx, body
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia uses type-as-constructor for casts: `Int64(x)` rather than C-style
`(int)x`. The emitter therefore writes the target type first followed
by parenthesised value.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads value (child 0) and target_type (child 1). Emits the target
type via emit_type, then `(`, then the value expression, then `)`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_cast" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Let value be proc node_child with node, 0
    Let target_type be proc node_child with node, 1

    proc emit_type with ctx, target_type
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "("
    proc emit_expression with ctx, value
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ")"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Julia interpolated strings use `"prefix $(expr) suffix"`. The HIR
represents an interpolated string as a sequence of alternating literal
and expression children; the emitter walks them in order, switching
between raw output and `$(...)` interpolation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits opening `"`. Loops children: if child node_type is HIR_LITERAL,
emits its value verbatim; otherwise wraps it in `$(...)` and recurses
emit_expression. Closes with `"`.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Literal chunks are emitted unescaped. Callers must ensure that the
HIR builder has properly escaped backslashes and double quotes in
literal segments before reaching this emitter.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "emit_interpolated_string" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    Note: Children alternate string-literal nodes and expression nodes.
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "\""
    Let count be proc node_child_count with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let part be proc node_child with node, i
        Let pt be proc node_type_of with part
        If pt is equal to HIR.HIR_LITERAL:
            Let str_ptr be proc node_value with part
            Let str_val be proc julia_string_from_pointer with str_ptr
            proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, str_val
        Otherwise:
            proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "$("
            proc emit_expression with ctx, part
            proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ")"
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "\""
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Type expressions occur in struct fields, parameter annotations, return
type annotations, and cast targets. Julia's type syntax differs
significantly from Runa's (e.g. Optional<T> -> Union{T, Nothing},
Array<T> -> Vector{T}), so each HIR type kind needs its own rendering
rule.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard emits `Any`. Dispatches on HIR type kind:
HIR_BASIC_TYPE -> mapped name via julia_map_basic_type;
HIR_OPTIONAL_TYPE -> `Union{T, Nothing}`;
HIR_ARRAY_TYPE -> `Vector{T}`;
HIR_TUPLE_TYPE -> `Tuple{T1, T2, ...}`;
HIR_GENERIC_TYPE -> `Mapped{arg1, arg2, ...}`;
HIR_UNION_TYPE -> `Union{T1, T2, ...}`;
HIR_FUNCTION_TYPE -> bare `Function` (Julia can't express full
signature in a type annotation without sigtuple objects).
Unknown kinds fall through to `Any`.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_type" takes ctx as EmitterContext, node as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "Any"
        Return
    End If

    Let nt be proc node_type_of with node

    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_BASIC_TYPE:
        Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
        Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr
        Let mapped be proc julia_map_basic_type with name_str
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, mapped
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_OPTIONAL_TYPE:
        Let inner be proc node_child with node, 0
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "Union{"
        proc emit_type with ctx, inner
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ", Nothing}"
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_ARRAY_TYPE:
        Let elem be proc node_child with node, 0
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "Vector{"
        proc emit_type with ctx, elem
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "}"
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_TUPLE_TYPE:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "Tuple{"
        Let count be proc node_child_count with node
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            If i is greater than 0:
                proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ", "
            End If
            Let elem be proc node_child with node, i
            proc emit_type with ctx, elem
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "}"
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_GENERIC_TYPE:
        Let name_ptr be proc node_value with node
        Let name_str be proc julia_string_from_pointer with name_ptr
        Let mapped be proc julia_map_basic_type with name_str
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, mapped
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "{"
        Let count be proc node_child_count with node
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            If i is greater than 0:
                proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ", "
            End If
            Let arg be proc node_child with node, i
            proc emit_type with ctx, arg
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "}"
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_UNION_TYPE:
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "Union{"
        Let count be proc node_child_count with node
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            If i is greater than 0:
                proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, ", "
            End If
            Let alt be proc node_child with node, i
            proc emit_type with ctx, alt
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "}"
        Return
    End If
    If nt is equal to HIR.HIR_FUNCTION_TYPE:
        Note: Julia function types render as `Function`; arg signatures aren't
        Note: expressible in Julia type annotations without sigtuple objects.
        proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "Function"
        Return
    End If

    proc emitter_emit from Emitter with ctx, "Any"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: OPERATOR MAPPING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Runa uses English-word operators (`plus`, `is equal to`) while Julia
uses the symbolic forms (`+`, `==`). This mapping table covers the
common arithmetic, comparison, and logical operators. Unknown opcodes
pass through unchanged so user-defined operators retain their spelling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Linear sequence of string_equals comparisons covering arithmetic
(plus, minus, multiplied by, divided by, modulo), comparison (is
equal to, is not equal to, is less than, is greater than, etc.),
logical (and, or), and bitwise (bitwise and/or/xor, shifted left/
right). Returns the mapped symbol on match, or the original op
string on no match.
@End Implementation

Process called "julia_map_binary_op" takes runa_op as String returns String:
    Let eq be 0

    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "plus"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "+"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "minus"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "-"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "multiplied by"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "*"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "divided by"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "/"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "modulo"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "%"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "is equal to"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "=="
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "is not equal to"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "!="
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "is less than"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "<"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "is greater than"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return ">"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "is less than or equal to"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "<="
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "is greater than or equal to"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return ">="
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "and"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "&&"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "or"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "||"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "bitwise and"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "&"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "bitwise or"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "|"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "bitwise xor"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "^"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "shifted left by"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "<<"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "shifted right by"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return ">>"
    End If

    Return runa_op
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary operator mapping mirrors the binary case but for prefix
operators. `negate` and `minus` both produce `-`, `not` becomes `!`,
`bitwise not` becomes `~`. Unknown opcodes pass through unchanged.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four string_equals comparisons: negate -> "-", minus -> "-",
not -> "!", bitwise not -> "~". Returns the mapped symbol on match,
or runa_op on no match.
@End Implementation

Process called "julia_map_unary_op" takes runa_op as String returns String:
    Let eq be 0

    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "negate"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "-"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "minus"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "-"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "not"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "!"
    End If
    Set eq to proc string_equals from StringCore with runa_op, "bitwise not"
    If eq is equal to 1:
        Return "~"
    End If

    Return runa_op
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRING POINTER COERCION
Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR value fields are Integer-typed pointers to null-terminated strings
Note: when they carry textual data. This helper centralizes the cast so the
Note: rest of the file reads as if value() always returned a String.
@Reasoning:
HIR.value slots are Integer-typed because the IR pre-dates a unified
string handle type. Centralising the Integer->String coercion in one
helper keeps the rest of this file readable, and gives one place to
add a null guard for safe traversal of nodes whose value happens to
be 0.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns the empty string. Otherwise returns the integer
verbatim — at this bootstrap layer the integer IS the string handle,
treated as a raw pointer to a null-terminated byte sequence consumed
by StringCore primitives.
@End Implementation

Process called "julia_string_from_pointer" takes ptr as Integer returns String:
    Note: In the bootstrap stage strings are represented as raw pointers to
    Note: null-terminated byte sequences. The pointer IS the string at this
    Note: layer; the cast is implicit in how the codegen passes it to
    Note: string_equals/string_concat. We just guard against null.
    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    Return ptr
End Process
